                <p>In the winter of 1946-1947, the biggest military mission ever to go to Antarctica left the US under strange circumstances. Operation Highjump, led by the famous polar explorer Rear Admiral Richard E. Byrd, had 4,700 people, 13 ships (including an aircraft carrier), 23 planes, and goals that are still being debated today. The official job was to train soldiers for war in the Arctic and make claims on land. But there are persistent rumors that the real reason is to look for secret Nazi bases buried in the ice, meet advanced disc-shaped ships, and find ways into a hollow earth where ancient civilizations live. What really went on in Antarctica during those exciting months? And why did the trip end so suddenly after only eight weeks instead of the planned six to eight months?</p>

                <div class="article-image-container">
