                <h2>The Nazi Connection: Neuschwabenland and Base 211</h2>

                <p>We need to look at what happened before Operation Highjump to understand it. In December 1938, Nazi Germany sent the ship <em>Schwabenland</em> on a secret trip to Antarctica. It arrived at Princess Martha Coast on January 19, 1939. The Germans took over a huge area that they called Neuschwabenland (New Swabia) after their ship. It was about 600,000 square kilometers of what Norway had already claimed as Queen Maud Land.</p>

                <p>The expedition's records show that they did a lot of aerial reconnaissance with two Dornier Wal seaplanes called "Passat" and "Boreas." These planes took more than 16,000 aerial photos and covered hundreds of thousands of square kilometers over the course of several weeks. It was said that the planes dropped aluminum darts with swastikas on them at important places to mark Germany's claims to land. However, members of the expedition later said that this only happened once, with all the darts being dropped at the same time.</p>

                <p>Conspiracy theorists used these simple facts to make up long stories. The most common claim is about "Base 211" (or Station 211), which is said to be a secret underground facility that the Nazis built in a warm, ice-free oasis that was found during the 1938-1939 expedition. These theories say that the base was about 250 kilometers inland, under the ice in caverns that were heated by geothermal energy and could be reached all year round.</p>

                <p>The truth is much less exciting. The German expedition spent about a month in Antarctic waters. That wasn't enough time for aerial surveys, let alone building an underground base 250 kilometers across uncharted, crevasse-filled terrain. Experienced explorers like Scott, Shackleton, and Amundsen built bases in Antarctica that took at least two weeks to put up surface structures for a dozen men. Those teams had the right experience.</p>

                <p>More importantly, the Dornier flying boats couldn't land on glaciers or ice caps, so they couldn't be used to move cargo to any inland location. It is still physically impossible to build even a small base so far inland in one month with untrained workers and no suitable transportation. Since the 1950s, more than 1,000 scientists have gone to the Neuschwabenland area, and research stations have been set up there. Satellite mapping has covered every square meter, but none of these have shown any signs of German construction during the war.</p>

                <p>In Dronning Maud Land, there are no geothermal caves that are said to hold Base 211. There are volcanoes and geothermal activity in other parts of Antarctica, but this area is especially quiet geologically. The ice-free areas in Antarctica are not warm; they are cold because of the winds and low snow deposition.</p>

                <h2>The Official Mission of Operation Highjump</h2>

                <p>Operation Highjump started on August 26, 1946, a little over a year after World War II ended. This was in the middle of a lot of speculation. The expedition's goals were simple: train naval personnel to work in polar conditions, test military equipment (especially helicopters) in harsh environments, establish a U.S. presence in Antarctica, see if ice could be used as a landing surface for planes, do geological surveys, and map large areas that had never been explored before.</p>

                <p>Admiral Byrd, who was already famous for his polar explorations, was in charge of the expedition. He was the first person to fly over the South Pole in 1929. Richard H. Cruzen, a rear admiral, was in charge of the task force. The huge operation was split into three groups: the Central Group, led by Byrd, worked on the Ross Ice Shelf, the Transantarctic Mountains, and the polar plateau; the Eastern Group looked at the coast between Little America and the Palmer Peninsula; and the Western Group looked at the coast of Antarctica south of Australia.</p>

                <p>The expedition built Little America IV near the Bay of Whales on the Ross Ice Shelf. It had Quonset huts, tents, and a few runways. Six R4D-5L planes (military DC-3s with skis) took off from the aircraft carrier USS Philippine Sea using rocket-assisted takeoff (JATO bottles) because the carrier deck was too short for normal takeoffs. These planes flew a lot of mapping missions, and two of them even flew over the South Pole itself-one with Admiral Byrd on board-and then on to areas that had never been explored before.</p>

                <p>No matter how you look at it, the results were great. The expedition mapped more than 1.5 million square miles of Antarctica and took more than 70,000 aerial photos of coastlines and interior features that no one had ever seen before. Helicopters showed how useful they could be in polar operations, which changed how the military plans to use them in the future in very cold places. Research archives were full of geological samples and weather data.</p>

                <h2>The Strange Early Withdrawal</h2>

                <p>Then, all of a sudden, the trip was over. The whole task force left in late February 1947, just eight weeks after they had planned to stay for six to eight months. Official reasons given were worsening weather, with the Antarctic winter approaching making it too dangerous to continue operations and putting ships at risk of getting stuck in quickly forming sea ice.</p>

                <p>This explanation has not satisfied many people who believe in conspiracies. Why would the world's largest Antarctic expedition, led by the most experienced polar explorer in history and with multiple icebreakers and thousands of experienced military personnel, have to turn back because of normal seasonal weather? The expedition got there in the middle of January 1947, which was already late in the short Antarctic summer. This suggests that they didn't plan well if the weather was the only reason for the retreat.</p>

                <p>In addition, the task force had the icebreaker USCGC Northwind (with USS Burton Island arriving late), destroyers, a submarine, and an aircraft carrier. This was not a fleet that could be easily stopped by ice. Some people who took part later said they were unhappy with the operation's lack of clear goals and organization, which made them think there were problems inside the organization that had nothing to do with the weather.</p>

                <p>In this uncertainty, different explanations thrived.</p>

                <h2>Admiral Byrd's Strange Words</h2>

                <p>An interview Admiral Byrd gave to journalist Lee Van Atta and published in the Chilean newspaper <em>El Mercurio</em> on March 5, 1947, added fuel to conspiracy theories. Byrd said things in this interview that were hard to understand and have been talked about a lot:</p>

                <blockquote>
                "Admiral Richard E. Byrd warned today that the United States should take steps to protect itself against the possibility of hostile aircraft invading the country from the polar regions. He said that in the event of a new war, the United States could be attacked by aircraft that can fly over one or both poles."
                </blockquote>

                <p>Byrd went on to say, "The world is shrinking at an amazing rate... This is one of the most important things I learned during my recent trip to Antarctica. I must warn my fellow countrymen that the time has come to stop relying on the fact that the oceans, the poles, and the distances will keep us safe."</p>

                <p>There are two ways to look at these statements, which were made right after Highjump came back. Skeptics point out that Byrd was warning about Soviet long-range bombers and how polar air routes made the US more vulnerable, which was a real worry at the start of the Cold War. The U.S. military was worried that the Soviet Union could attack from the Arctic, and part of the reason for Highjump was to train for operations in the Arctic against this threat.</p>

                <p>Conspiracy theorists read Byrd's words in a different way: "hostile aircraft from the polar regions" means advanced Nazi craft or UFOs that the expedition saw. The "fantastic speed" doesn't mean changes in world politics; it means how fast the disc-shaped craft that supposedly attacked the American fleet moved.</p>

